  "prompt": "What happens if we don't swing our hands when we walk?",
  "response": "When we don't swing our hands while walking, several things can happen:\n\n1. Balance and efficiency:\n- Hand swinging helps maintain balance and stability\n- It reduces energy expenditure during walking\n- Reduces the workload on leg muscles\n- Helps counterbalance body movements\n\n2. Biomechanical changes:\n- Walking becomes less natural and more rigid\n- Stride length and walking pattern may be altered\n- Increased effort required to maintain normal walking motion\n\n3. Potential physical effects:\n- More strain on leg and hip muscles\n- Slightly reduced walking speed\n- Potential increased risk of losing balance\n- May cause slight shoulder and back tension\n\n4. Neurological aspects:\n- Natural arm swing is connected to brain's motor coordination\n- Suppressing arm swing can feel unnatural and uncomfortable\n- May indicate underlying neurological conditions if arm swing is consistently absent\n\n5. Psychological impact:\n- Walking without arm swing might feel awkward\n- Can create self-consciousness about walking style\n\nThese effects can vary depending on individual physiology and walking conditions. Most people naturally swing their arms while walking without conscious effort.",
